ce:section.ce:para:
CQD is a promising candidate for developing active food packaging films as functional fillers due to its excellent antibacterial properties, antioxidant activity, and high compatibility with most biopolymers due to low toxicity and water solubility (Fig. 6
                        ). Composite films with CQDs impart antioxidant and antibacterial properties and enhance physicochemical properties such as mechanical, UV blocking, and gas barrier properties due to the formation of strong interactions between CQDs and polymer matrix through hydrophilic interactions. Table 1
                         summarizes the effects of CQD addition on the physical, chemical, and functional properties of CQD-added biodegradable food packaging films. So far, two methods have been mainly used to prepare antimicrobial CQD-based active films, including absorption/coating and solvent casting by direct incorporation [55,60]. When preparing CQD absorption/coating films, a polymer matrix is immersed in a CQD solvent to absorb CQDs on the surface through diffusion. High shear vortex mixing or sonication can contribute to the electrostatic interaction of CQDs, interactions between CQDs and polymer, and CQD absorption, which is highly dependent on the pore size of the polymer matrix. On the other hand, the most commonly used solution casting method is to prepare a film solution by dissolving the film components together with CQD in a solvent and then casting. However, if a concentration of CQD is too high, it may form aggregates in the film solution [14].
